│ The bug is an assertion failure in the loop vectorizer, triggered by a disagreement        │
│ between the new VPlan-based cost model and the older legacy cost model. The assertion is   │
│ designed to catch such disagreements, but it includes exceptions for cases where the       │
│ legacy model is known to be less reliable, such as loops with early exits or               │
│ non-compile-time-constant trip counts.                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ In the provided reproducer, the loop's trip count depends on a runtime value (`%n`),       │
│ making it a type of early-exit loop. The VPlan model correctly identifies this as a        │
│ candidate for vectorization (with a factor of 4), while the legacy model conservatively    │
│ decides against it (factor of 1). This disagreement should be permissible. However, the    │
│ flag `PlanForEarlyExitLoop`, which is intended to allow this discrepancy, is incorrectly   │
│ calculated as `false`.                                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause is that the calculation of `PlanForEarlyExitLoop` relies on the structure   │
│ of the VPlan's control-flow graph. Optimizations performed during VPlan construction can   │
│ simplify this graph, obscuring the original loop's early-exit nature and leading to the    │
│ incorrect flag value.                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ To fix this, I will make the check more robust by directly consulting the                  │
│ `LoopVectorizationLegality` analysis, which has already determined whether the original    │
│ loop has an early exit. By adding `Legal->hasUncountableEarlyExit()` to the condition, we  │
│ correctly identify the loop in the reproducer as one where the cost models are allowed to  │
│ disagree. This prevents the assertion from firing without affecting other vectorization    │
│ decisions.                                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```patch                                                                                   │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                      │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                      │
│ @@ -7575,9 +7575,10 @@                                                                     │
│    // Set PlanForEarlyExitLoop to true if the BestPlan has been built from a               │
│    // loop with an uncountable early exit. The legacy cost model doesn't                   │
│    // properly model costs for such loops.                                                 │
│ -  bool PlanForEarlyExitLoop =                                                             │
│ -      BestPlan.getVectorLoopRegion() &&                                                   │
│ -      BestPlan.getVectorLoopRegion()->getSingleSuccessor() !=                             │
│ -          BestPlan.getMiddleBlock();                                                      │
│ +  bool PlanForEarlyExitLoop = Legal->hasUncountableEarlyExit() ||                         │
│ +                              (BestPlan.getVectorLoopRegion() &&                          │
│ +                               BestPlan.getVectorLoopRegion()->getSingleSuccessor() !=    │
│ +                                   BestPlan.getMiddleBlock());                            │
│    assert((BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width || PlanForEarlyExitLoop ||                   │
│            planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(BestFactor.Width),             │
│                                                  CostCtx, OrigLoop) ||                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
